A crony capitalism, American-style.
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the U.S. Treasury Department and its IMF allies blamed the problems of this region on crony capitalism, a lack of transparency and an ineffective government?
Countries were encouraged to follow the American model, use American accounting firms, and introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
Regardless of having developed under the leadership of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia grew more rapidly than any other region – and with greater stability – over the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal lends a new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "One must be faultless to criticize others."
Enron employed large accounting schemes and complex financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
She used her money to acquire influence and power, shape the U.S. energy policy and exempt herself from regulations.
Crony capitalism is not new, nor is it the exclusive domain of one party.
The former U.S. Treasury Secretary, Robert Rubin, would have attempted to influence the current government to intervene on behalf of Enron in the disputed conflict in India.
When he was in office, he intervened when the supposedly independent accounting standards board attempted to clean up the accounting for executive compensation.
It's partly due to him that the effort to make corporate accounting more transparent has been hindered.
The enthusiasm of America to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free market is merely a thin veil for the well-being of old-established firms: giving to those who have the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron wasn't bailed out and the problems weren't revealed suggests the absence of crony capitalism.
My interpretation is different: this highlights the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can at least mitigate them.
When the press began to look into Enron, the number of Congress members who had accepted Enron money was disclosed.
These contributions to campaigns were not just about the public interest, but were investments.
Like most Enron investments, everything went well in the short term, but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons are to be drawn from this case.
Certain scandals related to politics, such as the Enron scandal, strengthen the arguments for campaign finance reform and the need for even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Business interests are sapping democracies, capable in fact of buying elections.
The Bush administration has, however, refused to disclose information that would confirm the role of business interests in shaping its energy policy.
Other lessons pertain to the economy, more specifically to the information economy.
For markets to function properly, for the right signals to be provided to efficiently allocate resources, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as rosy a picture as possible.
Accounting controls are intended to place limits on potential abuses.
But who will guard the guardians ?
Who will control the account controllers?
We rely heavily on motivations.
Auditors wish to preserve their reputation.
But the relationship between advisory practices and accounting controls brings about other distorted motivations: a motivation to please clients who dislike unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within accounting firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of controls could be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the unsung hero of the debacle.
But accounting firms and their corporate clients - which is hardly surprising given the cabal that has developed - have strongly attacked his proposal to separate advisory and accounting control activities.
What Levitt understood - and the Enron debacle has so clearly shown - is that motivations are important, but unregulated markets cannot by themselves provide the best motivations.
Markets cannot provide motivations for wealth creation; they can provide motivations for the type of deals that Enron was involved in.
The new economy - and its new, complex financial instruments - highlights the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make it easier to obfuscate them.
Rather than confronting the problems, American business systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by crony capitalism of the American variety.
The major problem of our time is finding the right balance between government and the market.
The status quo will claim that Enron was an exception: that its demise was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud and that those who break these laws must face consequences and will face them.
But the vast majority of Enron's actions were lawful.
Its auditors claim that its central practices complied with the law and that thousands of other companies act the same way.
They are right - and that's exactly the problem.
Investors need to be assured that the information received accurately reflects the company's economic situation.
Under the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors have no possibility of being offered these assurances at present.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check the motivations.
We can attempt to instill better ethical standards.
But we can't count on them when so many people around the world are unbothered by the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we find that they manage them in their own interests.
But even when evidence of such abuses becomes evident, new venues for abuse are repeatedly created - take the American repeal of the Glass Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investments.
We have repeatedly observed the consequences of the excesses of unbridled market freedom.
We must now resist the temptation of tilting toward the other extreme.
The challenge lies in striking a fair balance.
